    <h4>18 September 2012</h4>
    <h2>Mixel for iPhone</h2>
    
    <div class="columns">
      <p>At <a href="http://mixel.cc">Mixel</a> we just launched our iPhone app, which was recently featured in the <a href="https://itunes.apple.com/app/mixel-for-iphone/id549650476">App Store</a>. The app lets you easily combine pictures, add filters and share collages to Mixel or other networks.</p>
      
      <p>We knew the iPhone app had to be more than a simple port of our previous iPad app. For example, cropping images with your finger didn&apos;t seem as attractive on the phone&apos;s smaller screen. So instead we created a <em>shuffle</em> feature. Users add their photos and press the <em>shuffle</em> button until they are happy with the results. Thanks to <a href="https://twitter.com/aleffert">Akiva</a>, this works very smoothly.</p>

      <p>We also noticed that the <em>remix</em> feature in the Mixel iPad app made users hesitant to share their personal photos. So we removed it, opting instead for an album feature that allowed users who follow each other to create albums together &ndash; sharing whole collages instead of collage pieces.</p>

      <p>It was particularly fun to add a colorful, animated gradient to the nav and toolbars. Each tab has its own base color that animates at the top of the otherwise white Mixel UI.</p>

    
    </div><!-- .columns -->
  </div><!-- .copy -->
</div><!-- .post -->











